¬ß Sums and differences ‚¶â
¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ The ‚ù¨sum‚ù≠ (or ‚ù¨Minkowski sum‚ù≠) of two sets $S, T ‚äÇ ùó•^n$
    is the set
    ‚óá ‚¶ä
      ‚Äñ \Set{z ‚àà ùó•^n}{(‚àÉx ‚àà S)(‚àÉy ‚àà T)(z = x + y)}. ‚¶â
    ‚¶â‚¶â

  ‚Äñ Likewise, the ‚ù¨difference‚ù≠ (or ‚ù¨Minkowski difference‚ù≠) of two
    sets $S, T ‚äÇ ùó•^n$ is the set
    ‚óá ‚¶ä
      ‚Äñ \Set{z ‚àà ùó•^n}{(‚àÉx ‚àà S)(‚àÉy ‚àà T)(z = x - y)}. ‚¶â
    ‚¶â‚¶â
‚¶â

¬ß¬ß Notation ‚¶â
¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ We denote the sum of $S$ and $T$ by $S + T$, and the
    difference by $S - T$.
    ‚Ä† ‚¶ä
      ‚Äñ This second notation unfortunately conflicts with our
        notation for set differences. ‚¶â

      ‚Äñ Future editions will correct. ‚¶â
    ‚¶â‚¶â

  ‚Äñ We often use the slick notation
    ‚óá ‚¶ä
      ‚Äñ \Set{x + y}{x ‚àà S, y ‚àà T} \text{ and } \Set{x - y}{x
        ‚àà S, y ‚àà T}, ‚¶â
    ‚¶â
    for these two sets. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ Notice that in this notation
    ‚óá ‚¶ä
      ‚Äñ \set{a} + B = a + B ‚¶â
    ‚¶â‚¶â
‚¶â

